Pre-training is the initial and most computationally expensive phase of creating a chat AI system, where the model learns general language patterns by processing enormous quantities of text from books, websites, articles, and other sources.
During this phase, which can take weeks or months on thousands of specialized computer chips, the model repeatedly tries to predict what word comes next in sentences, gradually adjusting billions of internal parameters until it becomes remarkably good at understanding language structure, facts about the world, and how ideas connect.
This pre-training phase is what gives models like ChatGPT and Claude their broad knowledge base and language capabilities, though the raw pre-trained model isn't yet refined enough to be a helpful assistant—that requires additional training steps afterward.
